public class Logger {
    public enum LogLevel {
        LOGGER_INFO,
        LOGGER_WARNING,
        LOGGER_ERROR
    }

    public void log(LogLevel level, String message, Object... args) {
        switch (level) {
            case LOGGER_INFO:
                System.out.printf("INFO: " + message + "\n", args);
                break;
            case LOGGER_WARNING:
                System.out.printf("WARNING: " + message + "\n", args);
                break;
            case LOGGER_ERROR:
                System.out.printf("ERROR: " + message + "\n", args);
                break;
            default:
                System.out.println("Unknown log level");
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Logger logger = new Logger();
        logger.log(Logger.LogLevel.LOGGER_INFO, "is equivalent.");
        logger.log(Logger.LogLevel.LOGGER_WARNING, "results in counterexample %s.", "counterexampleValue");
        logger.log(Logger.LogLevel.LOGGER_ERROR, "An error occurred: %s", "errorDetails");
    }
}
```

In the solution, we define an enumeration `LogLevel` to represent the different log levels. The `Logger` class has a `log` method that takes a log level, a message, and variable arguments. Depending on the log level, it formats and outputs the log message using `System.out.printf`. In the `main` method, we demonstrate the usage of the `Logger` class by logging messages with different log levels and variable arguments.

